3 Further data cleaning: removing and re-arranging locations

Deleting municipalities that are not in the study (Beiarn county and Guovdageaidnu-Kautokeino) Re-estimating landings for the municipalities that were merged (Bodo + Skjerstad_2005, Bjarkoy_2013 + Harstad_2013) - I sum the landings for these pairs of municipalities for the years before theyve merged. Using this approach to merge catches will create duplicated rows, I remove them in the chunk after.

fish_nor_prep <- fish_nor %>% 
                  rename(Species = English) %>% 
                  mutate(Municip_name = as.character(Municip_name)) %>% 
                  filter(!Municip_name %in% c("Beiarn", "Guovdageaidnu-Kautokeino")) %>% 
                  mutate(newid = case_when(Municip_name %in% c("Harstad_2013", "Bjarkoy_2013") ~ "1",
                                           Municip_name %in% c("Bodo", "Skjerstad_2005") ~ "2",
                                           TRUE ~ Municip_name)) %>% 
                  group_by(newid, Year, Species) %>%  
                  mutate(Total_catch_new = sum(Total_catch))

In this table, Municip_name_new are the names of the municipalities after theyve merged. Total_catch_new is the total fish landings after municipalities merged.

fish_nor_prep2 <- fish_nor_prep %>% 
                  ungroup() %>% 
                  select(-c("Municip_name", "Total_catch")) %>% 
                  mutate(Municip_name_new = newid) %>% 
                  mutate(Municip_name_new = replace(Municip_name_new, Municip_name_new == "1", "Harstad")) %>% 
                  mutate(Municip_number = replace(Municip_number, Municip_name_new == "Harstad", "1903")) %>% 
                  mutate(Municip_name_new = replace(Municip_name_new, Municip_name_new == "2", "Bodo")) %>% 
                  mutate(Municip_number = replace(Municip_number, Municip_name_new == "Bodo", "1804")) %>% 
                  distinct_all() %>% 
                  select(-c(newid,  species_name))

5 Estimating cacth per area and maximal weighted catch

(Check fisheries README. for details). This approach however, has a danger of positive outliers dominating the maximal catch per area. Due to multiple reasons, catch will vary in every municipality for each stock from year to year. Thus, a maximal catch (biomass) per area can be just an outlier, a seldom seen very high catch. Therefore most of the biomass.area/max.biomass.area ratios are very low (75% are less than 0.6). The largest catch per sea area was observed in ksnes in 2018, for Atlantic cod.

We do not have MSY-reference points for shrimp, but we can assume it is sustainable. https://www.hi.no/hi/temasider/arter/kyst-og-fjordreke Similarly, for Kingcrab, I will assume its catches sustainable.

I remove redfish, blue whiting and greenland halibut from the table. 17.02.2020 we decided not to include these three species into the Fisheries sub-goal.

Calculation catch weighted scores (proportional catch multiplied by the stock score).

seaarea <- seaarea %>% 
          mutate(Komnum = as.character(Komnum))   

weighted_catch_score <- fish_nor_prep2 %>%
  filter(!Species %in%
    c(
      "Redfish",
      "Greenland halibut",
       "Blue whiting"
    )) %>%
  mutate(stock_score = replace(
    stock_score,
    Species == "Shrimp",
    1
  )) %>%
  mutate(stock_score = replace(
    stock_score,
    Species == "Kingcrab",
    1
  )) %>%
  left_join(seaarea[, c("Havflate", "Komnum")], by = c("Municip_number" = "Komnum")) %>%
  rename("Seaarea" = "Havflate") %>%
  mutate(catch_per_area = Total_catch_new / Seaarea) %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  mutate(max_catch_area = max(catch_per_area)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(weighted_catch =  catch_per_area / max_catch_area) %>%
  mutate(weighted_catch_score = weighted_catch * stock_score)
#Check the basic stats for weighted biomass score:
mosaic::fav_stats(weighted_catch_score$catch_per_area)

6 Re-estimate weighted catch per area based on smoothed catches

6.1 Apply 3-years rolling mean on catch data

Rolling mean is a remedy against inter-annual variability in catches and against influential outliers. I apply 3-year rolling mean to catch data. However,rolling mean does not help to smooth variability in catches between the municipalities.

When we apply a rolling mean, some observations will become NA (those at the edges of the 3-year window), because rollapply function calculates means of 3 overlapping years. Out of 8330 observations of catch, 1086 will become NA. The NAs are the first and the last year of a dataframe, made by unique combination of species and municipality. Since, there is certainly a temporal increase the total catches (taking a mean of all would be wrong), the best is to replace NA with the closest non-NA value, for instance for year 1994, take the catch of year 1995. I will do that with a zoo::na.fill function.

A simple function, that takes a dataframe as an argument, checks the number of rows. It applies 3-years running mean only of dataframe has at least 6 rows of data, and does not change the values if there are less than 6 rows of data.

runmean_on_df <- function(df, col){
  if (nrow(df) >= 6) {
    runmean <- rollapply(df[,col], width = 3, FUN = mean,  fill=list("extend"))
    df2 <-cbind(df, runmean)
  } else {
    runmean <-df[,col]
    df2 <-cbind(df, runmean)
  }
  df2
}
municipalities <-unique(fish_nor_prep2$Municip_name_new)
species <-unique(fish_nor_prep2$Species)

splist <-list()
finallist <-list()
for (i in 1:length(municipalities)) 
  {
   mp <- municipalities[i]
   df.mp <- fish_nor_prep2 %>% 
      filter(Municip_name_new == mp)
    for (j in 1:length(species))
     {
        sp <- species[j]
        df.sp <- df.mp %>% 
            filter(Species == sp)
  
      #runmean <-data.frame(catch_runmean = rollapply(df.sp$Total_catch_new, width = 3, FUN = mean,  fill=NA))
      df.sp.runmean <- runmean_on_df(as.data.frame(df.sp), 14) #column 14 is Total_catch_new
      #df.sp.full <- bind_cols(df.sp, runmean)
      splist[[j]] <- df.sp.runmean
      smoothed_catches_spp <- do.call("rbind", splist)
      finallist[[i]] <-smoothed_catches_spp
    
    }
   
 }
 
smoothed_catches <- do.call("rbind", finallist) %>% 
  rename(catch_runmean = runmean)
colSums(is.na(smoothed_catches))

6.2 Re-esitmate weighted catch per area based on smoothed catches

Since we remove three species, the resultant dataset is shorter - now with 6091 number of rows. For the calculation of catch weighted score, I use maximal catch observed in a given year per species.

smoothed_weighted_catch_score <- smoothed_catches %>%
  filter(!Species %in%
    c(
      "Redfish",
      "Greenland halibut",
      "Blue whiting"
    )) %>%
  mutate(stock_score = replace(
    stock_score,
    Species == "Shrimp",
    1
  )) %>%
  mutate(stock_score = replace(
    stock_score,
    Species == "Kingcrab",
    1
  )) %>% 
left_join(seaarea[, c("Havflate", "Komnum")], by = c("Municip_number" = "Komnum")) %>%
  rename("Seaarea" = "Havflate") %>%
  filter(!is.na(catch_runmean)) %>%
  mutate(catch_per_area = catch_runmean / Seaarea) %>%
  group_by(Year,Species) %>%
  mutate(max_catch_area = max(catch_per_area)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(weighted_catch = catch_per_area / max_catch_area) %>%
  mutate(weighted_catch_score = weighted_catch * stock_score)

#write.csv(smoothed_weighted_catch_score, "data/ smoothed_area_weighted_catch_and_catchscore.csv", row.names = F)

7.2 Summarize smoothed catches in a table

species <-unique(smoothed_weighted_catch_score$Species)

outputdf <- list()
for (i in 1:length(species))
  {
   sp <- species[i]
   spdf <- filter(smoothed_weighted_catch_score, Species == sp)
   stats <- mosaic::fav_stats(spdf$catch_per_area)
   allstats <-cbind(stats, Species = rep(sp, 1))
   outputdf[[i]] <- allstats
}

catch_area_favstats <- do.call("rbind", outputdf)

newtable <- catch_area_favstats %>%  
    mutate(Species = cell_spec(
    Species, color = "white", bold = T,
    background = spec_color(1:8, end = 0.9, option = "A", direction = -1))) %>% 
    mutate(max = round(max, 2)) %>% 
    mutate(max = cell_spec(
    as.numeric(max), "html", 
    color = ifelse(max > 1000, "red", "blue"))) %>% 
    kable(escape = F, align = "c", digits = 4) %>%
    kable_styling(c("striped", "condensed"), full_width = F) %>% 
    column_spec(1:10,bold = T,background = "azure", color = "darkgreen")

8 Calculate final fisheries scores based on smoothed weighted catches per area

final_scores_smoothed_area <- smoothed_weighted_catch_score %>%
  group_by(Year, Municip_number, Municip_name_new) %>%
  mutate(total_tons = sum(catch_runmean)) %>%
  mutate(catch_prop = catch_runmean / total_tons) %>%
  mutate(fish_score = sum(weighted_catch_score * catch_prop * 100))

10 Using 0.75th quartile of catch per area as a target

smoothed_weighted_catch_score_q75 <- smoothed_catches %>%
  filter(!Species %in%
    c(
      "Redfish",
      "Greenland halibut",
      "Blue whiting"
    )) %>%
  mutate(stock_score = replace(
    stock_score,
    Species == "Shrimp",
    1
  )) %>%
  mutate(stock_score = replace(
    stock_score,
    Species == "Kingcrab",
    1
  )) %>%
  left_join(seaarea[, c("Havflate", "Komnum")], by = c("Municip_number" = "Komnum")) %>%
  rename("Seaarea" = "Havflate") %>%
  filter(!is.na(catch_runmean)) %>%
  mutate(catch_per_area = catch_runmean / Seaarea) %>%
  group_by(Year,Species) %>%
  mutate(catch_area_q75 = quantile(catch_per_area, probs = 0.75)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(weighted_catch = ifelse(
    catch_per_area > catch_area_q75, 1, catch_per_area / catch_area_q75
  )) %>%
  mutate(weighted_catch_score = weighted_catch * stock_score)
